comments: Valanciunas (NOP) makes marginal contact with Capela (ATL) as he moves in the same direction toward the perimeter. The contact does not affect Capela's FOM.
Capela (ATL) establishes himself in a wide screening position and makes foot to foot contact with Graham (NOP), which dislodges him from his defensive position.
Graham (NOP) is already in Hunter's (ATL) path when contact occurs and he does not deliver contact.

Jones (NOP) gathers the ball on his right foot and takes his first step on his left foot.  As he takes his second step on his right foot, his left foot legally drags behind him as he elevates for the shot attempt.
Jones (NOP) is moving alongside Young's (ATL) path and maintains a legal guarding position at the end of the drive.
Graham (NOP) legally contests Bogdanovic's (ATL) jump shot attempt.
Ingram (NOP) does not abnormally or overtly extend his leg into Capela (ATL) during his jump shot attempt, and contact is marginal.
Capela (ATL) legally contests Ingram's (NOP) jump shot attempt.
Capela (ATL) does not make contact with the ball on his shot contest and therefore the ball is last touched by Ingram (NOP) before going out of bounds.  Possession is correctly awarded to Atlanta.

Jones (NOP) extends his arm out for the ball and marginal contact occurs as he brushes Young's (ATL) chin when he quickly changes directions. Contact to an opponent's head/face can be deemed marginal when the result of a natural basketball move, provided the contact is not disproportionate or uncontrolled.
Valanciunas (NOP) has a resting forearm to Collins' (ATL) front and the contact is marginal during his putback dunk.
Bogdanovic (ATL) moves forward into Jones' (NOP) body and delivers contact that affects his shot near the rim.
Marshall (NOP) is moving alongside Young's (ATL) path and legally contests the driving shot attempt.
Marshall (NOP) makes contact to Collins' (ATL) arm prior to making any contact with the ball, and the contact causes Collins to lose possession.
Collins (ATL) establishes himself in a screening position in Jones' (NOP) path and absorbs the contact.

Jones (NOP) is retreating his arm away from Collins' (ATL) path as they disengage, and some contact occurs with Collins' head.  Contact to an opponent's head/face can be deemed marginal when the result of a natural basketball move, provided the contact is not disproportionate or uncontrolled.
Ingram (NOP) momentarily places two hands on Young (ATL) and immediately removes them without affecting his SQBR.
Capela (ATL) jumps vertically and maintains a legal vertical position while absorbing the contact caused by Graham (NOP) as he contests the driving shot attempt.
Bogdanovic (ATL) pokes the ball away from Ingram (NOP) and is the last player to touch it before it goes out of bounds.
Valanciunas (NOP) establishes himself in a screening position in Hunter's (ATL) path and absorbs the contact.
Hunter (ATL) is moving alongside Ingram's (NOP) path and maintains a legal guarding position as he defends the drive.
Hunter (ATL) legally contests Ingram's (NOP) jump shot attempt.  Any "high-five" contact after the release is considered incidental.
Ingram (NOP) initiates any marginal contact after the release on his jump shot attempt by somewhat extending his leg out.

call_type: Turnover: Lost Ball Out of Bounds
comments: Capela (ATL) makes clean with the ball to dislodge it from Murphy III (NOP) and the ball rolls off of Murphy III's leg before going out of bounds.  Possession is correctly awarded to Atlanta.
During the rebound, Valanciunas (NOP) and Capela (ATL) mutually engage and disengage and the contact is marginal.
Jones (NOP) commits a take foul on Young (ATL).
